Session 15: Sniffing, ARP Poisoning, MAC Flooding, DNS Spoofing
ðŸ”¹ BASIC MCQs (10)

Sniffing is the process of:
A. Blocking traffic
B. Capturing network packets
C. Encrypting data
D. Filtering logs

Which protocol is MOST vulnerable to sniffing?
A. HTTPS
B. SSH
C. FTP
D. SSL

Passive sniffing means:
A. Injecting packets
B. Only listening to traffic
C. Modifying packets
D. Dropping packets

Active sniffing requires:
A. Hub
B. Switch manipulation
C. Encrypted traffic
D. VPN

ARP poisoning is used to:
A. Encrypt ARP packets
B. Redirect traffic
C. Block DNS
D. Flood MAC table

Ethereal (Wireshark) is mainly used for:
A. Exploitation
B. Packet capture and analysis
C. Password cracking
D. Port scanning

MAC flooding targets:
A. Routers
B. Switch CAM table
C. DNS servers
D. Firewalls

DNS spoofing results in:
A. Correct IP resolution
B. Fake IP resolution
C. Faster DNS
D. Encrypted DNS

Sniffing primarily threatens:
A. Availability
B. Integrity
C. Confidentiality
D. Authentication

Which is a sniffing countermeasure?
A. Plain HTTP
B. Encryption
C. MAC flooding
D. ARP poisoning

